27/11/2007
Slovenian Prime Minister Janez Jansa met with his Turkish counterpart, Recep Tayyip Erdogan, in Ankara on Wednesday (November 21st).
Jansa said the Slovenian public strongly supports Turkey's EU aspirations.
He pledged that his government will seek to open new chapters in Turkey's accession negotiations when Ljubljana assumes the rotating presidency in January.
Serbian Foreign Minister Vuk Jeremic met with his Russian counterpart, Sergey Lavrov, in Moscow on Thursday (November 22nd).
Lavrov stressed Russia's firm support for Belgrade's position on Kosovo's status.
Jeremic said his side is prepared to make a new concession, but cautioned that this would still fall under Serbia's proposal for broad autonomy instead of independence.
Greek Foreign Minister Dora Bakoyannis and <b>Romanian</b> counterpart Adrian Cioroianu warned on Thursday (November 22nd) against a unilateral proclamation of independence in Kosovo.
The two ministers stressed their countries' common position on Kosovo.
Greek Cypriot Parliament Speaker Demetris Christofias Karamanlis held separate meetings with Greek President Karolos Papoulias and Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis on Monday (November 19th) in Greece.
The Cyprus issue, Turkey's EU bid and the situation on the divided island were the main topics of discussion.
Albanian Foreign Minister Lulzim Basha met with his Montenegrin counterpart, Milan Rocen, on Thursday (November 22nd) in Tirana.
They discussed possibilities to expand political and economic co-operation between the countries and the Kosovo status issue.
Rocen also met with Prime Minister Sali Berisha, who applauded Montenegro's progress in its EU integration and economic development.
Macedonian President Branko Crvenkovski was in Belgrade on Thursday (November 22nd), meeting with Serbian counterpart Boris Tadic.
Talks focused on bilateral relations, security in the region and the negotiations on the future status of Kosovo.
(Various sources 20/11/07-27/11/07)
